<!-- ════════════════ ARTICLE BODY ════════════════ -->
<section class="art-body">
    <div class="art-content">
        <a href="/insights" class="art-back">
            <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none"><path d="M13 8H3m0 0l4-4M3 8l4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
            Back to Insights
        </a>

        <p class="art-lead">Every year, foundations lose donors. Not because those donors stopped caring about the mission &mdash; but because nobody noticed they stopped giving. By the time someone checks, the relationship has cooled, the donor has moved on, and the revenue is gone. LYBUNT and SYBUNT reports exist to catch this before it happens.</p>

        <p>These two reports are among the most important tools in any fundraiser&rsquo;s analytics toolkit. They surface the donors who are quietly slipping away, quantify the revenue at risk, and give your team a concrete list of people to call, email, or visit &mdash; before it&rsquo;s too late.</p>

        <h2>The Acronyms, Decoded</h2>

        <p>The names sound like nonsense. They&rsquo;re not &mdash; they&rsquo;re just brutally honest.</p>

        <p><strong>LYBUNT</strong> stands for <strong>Last Year But Unfortunately Not This</strong> year. These are donors who gave during your previous fiscal year but have not yet made a gift in the current fiscal year. If your fiscal year runs April to March, a LYBUNT donor is someone who gave between April 2025 and March 2026 but has given nothing since April 2026.</p>

        <p><strong>SYBUNT</strong> stands for <strong>Some Year But Unfortunately Not This</strong> year. These are donors who gave at some point in the past &mdash; but not in the current fiscal year <em>or</em> the prior fiscal year. They&rsquo;ve been gone longer than LYBUNTs, and the relationship has had more time to fade.</p>

        <div class="art-callout">
            <strong>Example:</strong> Margaret Wilson gave $15,000 to your annual campaign in FY2025. It&rsquo;s now October 2026, and she hasn&rsquo;t given anything this fiscal year. Margaret is a <strong>LYBUNT donor</strong> &mdash; and her $15,000 is revenue at risk. If she doesn&rsquo;t give in FY2026 or FY2027, she becomes a SYBUNT. If your team doesn&rsquo;t reach out, she eventually becomes a statistic.
        </div>

        <h2>Why These Reports Matter</h2>

        <p>Donor attrition is the silent killer of fundraising programs. Unlike a failed event or a rejected grant, lapsed donors don&rsquo;t send a notification. There&rsquo;s no alert, no declined payment, no angry email. They simply &hellip; stop. And in the noise of an active fiscal year &mdash; new campaigns, events, board meetings &mdash; their absence goes unnoticed.</p>

        <p>The math is straightforward and alarming. If your average LYBUNT donor gave $1,700 last year and you have 247 of them, that&rsquo;s <strong>$419,900 in annual revenue at risk</strong>. That&rsquo;s not hypothetical revenue. These are people who already demonstrated they believe in your mission enough to write a check. Losing them is a choice &mdash; the choice not to look.</p>

        <div class="art-callout-warn art-callout">
            <strong>The retention math:</strong> Industry research consistently shows it costs 5&ndash;7x more to acquire a new donor than to retain an existing one. First-time donor retention rates hover around 25&ndash;30%, while retained donor rates are 60&ndash;70%. Every dollar spent reactivating a LYBUNT is worth significantly more than a dollar spent acquiring a stranger.
        </div>

        <p>This is why LYBUNT/SYBUNT reports aren&rsquo;t just &ldquo;nice to have&rdquo; analytics. They&rsquo;re operational tools. A report that sits in a dashboard unread is worthless. A report that generates a call list for your Major Gifts officer on Monday morning &mdash; that&rsquo;s the difference between recovering $50,000 and losing it.</p>

        <h2>What a LYBUNT / SYBUNT Report Should Include</h2>

        <p>A useful LYBUNT/SYBUNT report isn&rsquo;t just a list of names. It needs enough context for your team to prioritize outreach and personalize every conversation. Here&rsquo;s what it should contain:</p>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>Donor name</strong> and contact information</li>
            <li><strong>Classification</strong> &mdash; LYBUNT or SYBUNT</li>
            <li><strong>Last gift date</strong> and <strong>last gift amount</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Lifetime giving</strong> &mdash; total historical contributions</li>
            <li><strong>Number of gifts</strong> &mdash; frequency indicates engagement depth</li>
            <li><strong>Revenue at risk</strong> &mdash; what they gave last year (the amount you&rsquo;ll lose)</li>
            <li><strong>Giving band breakdown</strong> &mdash; $25K+ LYBUNTs are more urgent than $50 LYBUNTs</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Here&rsquo;s what this looks like in practice:</p>

