        <p>Notice the report doesn&rsquo;t just list names &mdash; it tells a story. RBC Foundation gave $25,000 last year and has $180,000 in lifetime giving across 12 gifts. That&rsquo;s a deeply engaged partner who hasn&rsquo;t renewed. That&rsquo;s a phone call, not an email. David Chen, on the other hand, is a SYBUNT &mdash; his last gift was May 2024, over two years ago. He needs a different conversation entirely.</p>

        <h2>LYBUNT vs. SYBUNT &mdash; When to Prioritize</h2>

        <p>Not all lapsed donors are equal. The distinction between LYBUNT and SYBUNT isn&rsquo;t just academic &mdash; it should drive your outreach strategy.</p>

        <h3>LYBUNT donors: the warm leads</h3>

        <p>LYBUNT donors gave recently. The relationship is still warm. They know your organization, they&rsquo;ve seen your impact, and they made a conscious decision to support you within the last 12&ndash;18 months. Something interrupted their pattern &mdash; maybe they forgot, maybe life got busy, maybe they didn&rsquo;t receive a compelling ask. These are your highest-probability recoveries.</p>

        <p>For high-value LYBUNTs ($5,000+), the response should be personal and immediate: a phone call from the fundraiser who knows them, a handwritten note from the executive director, or an in-person visit. For mid-range LYBUNTs ($500&ndash;$5,000), a personalized email that references their specific last gift and its impact is appropriate. Don&rsquo;t send a generic appeal &mdash; they&rsquo;ll see through it.</p>

        <h3>SYBUNT donors: the reactivation project</h3>

        <p>SYBUNT donors have been gone for two or more fiscal years. The relationship has cooled significantly. Reactivating them requires a different approach: remind them why they cared in the first place. Impact stories, organizational milestones, and &ldquo;here&rsquo;s what&rsquo;s changed since you last gave&rdquo; messaging tends to work better than a standard ask.</p>

        <div class="art-callout">
            <strong>Prioritization rule of thumb:</strong> Always work LYBUNT before SYBUNT. Within each category, prioritize by lifetime value. A LYBUNT donor with $180,000 in lifetime giving should be at the top of your call list &mdash; not buried in a batch email with 200 other names.
        </div>

        <h2>Turning the Report into Action</h2>

        <p>A LYBUNT/SYBUNT report is only valuable if it changes what your team does on Monday morning. Here&rsquo;s a practical workflow:</p>

        <ol class="art-steps">
            <li>
                <strong>Export and segment</strong>
                Pull the report and segment by giving level. Create separate lists for $10K+, $1K&ndash;$10K, $250&ndash;$1K, and under $250. Each tier gets a different outreach strategy and different team members.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Personal outreach for high-value LYBUNTs ($5K+)</strong>
                These donors warrant a phone call or in-person meeting. Before calling, review their giving history, last interaction, and any notes in your CRM. Reference their specific impact: &ldquo;Your $15,000 gift funded 14 scholarships last year &mdash; I wanted to share how those students are doing.&rdquo;
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Targeted appeal for mid-range LYBUNTs ($500&ndash;$5K)</strong>
                Send a personalized email that names their last gift amount, the campaign it supported, and the impact it had. Include a specific ask amount at or slightly above their last gift. Make it easy to give &mdash; one click to an online donation form.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Automated re-engagement for smaller donors</strong>
                For donors under $500, design a 3-email re-engagement series: (1) impact update with no ask, (2) &ldquo;here&rsquo;s what we&rsquo;re working on next&rdquo; with a soft ask, (3) a direct, time-limited appeal. Space them 7&ndash;10 days apart.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>SYBUNT reactivation campaign</strong>
                For SYBUNT donors, the messaging shifts from &ldquo;renew your support&rdquo; to &ldquo;a lot has changed &mdash; here&rsquo;s why now is a great time to reconnect.&rdquo; Lead with organizational milestones and new programs. These donors need to be re-sold on the mission.
            </li>
        </ol>

        <h2>How Fund-Raise Handles This</h2>

        <p>If you&rsquo;re running Blackbaud RE NXT and using Fund-Raise, your LYBUNT/SYBUNT report is already built. The moment you import your data, Fund-Raise calculates every donor&rsquo;s status across fiscal years and surfaces the complete list &mdash; with revenue at risk, giving bands, and department breakdowns.</p>

        <p>The dashboard shows summary KPIs (total LYBUNT count, total SYBUNT count, combined revenue at risk) alongside a filterable table you can sort by last gift amount, lifetime value, or last gift date. Need to drill down? Ask Fund-Raise&rsquo;s AI assistant: <em>&ldquo;Show me all LYBUNTs with lifetime giving over $50K&rdquo;</em> &mdash; and you&rsquo;ll get an instant, sortable list.</p>

        <p>When you&rsquo;re ready to act, export the filtered list as a CSV for mail merge, or generate a one-click PDF report for your board or department head. The LYBUNT/SYBUNT PDF is one of 10 reports Fund-Raise generates automatically &mdash; no Crystal Reports, no SQL, no BI developer required.</p>

        <h2>The Cost of Not Looking</h2>

        <p>Every day you don&rsquo;t run a LYBUNT/SYBUNT report, donors are drifting further away. The longer a lapsed donor goes without contact, the less likely they are to return. A LYBUNT who hasn&rsquo;t heard from you in three months is recoverable. A SYBUNT who hasn&rsquo;t heard from you in two years is a long shot.</p>

        <p>The data is already in your CRM. The donors are already on the list. The only question is whether someone is looking &mdash; and whether they&rsquo;re looking in time.</p>

